# Custom Wazuh Detection Rule — Foreign IP Login Attempt

## What this is
Authored a custom Wazuh rule to detect SSH login attempts from IPs
outside the trusted network, deployed it to the manager, and validated
it fires correctly against a simulated attack.

## The rule (local_rules.xml)
\`\`\`xml
<rule id="100200" level="7">
  <if_sid>5760</if_sid>
  <description>Login attempt from foreign IP detected</description>
  <group>geoip,authentication,</group>
</rule>
\`\`\`

## What I did
1. Added the rule as a child of Wazuh's built-in SSH auth-failure rule.
2. Debugged a silent failure: the example used parent rule ID 5716,
   but that rule never actually matched this log format — swapped to
   5760, which is what Wazuh's decoder actually fires on.
3. Restarted the Wazuh manager/cluster to load the new rule.
4. Generated a synthetic SSH failure log from an external IP (8.8.8.8)
   and ran it through the Ruleset Test tool.
5. Confirmed rule 100200 fired as expected, tagged with `geoip` and
   `authentication` groups.

## Result
\`\`\`
Phase 3: Completed filtering (rules).
  id: '100200'
  level: '7'
  description: 'Login attempt from foreign IP detected'
  firedtimes: '1'
  Alert to be generated.
\`\`\`

## Key takeaway
Copy-pasted tutorial rule IDs don't always match your actual decoder
output — always validate against the ruleset test tool before assuming
a rule works.

